@Node "Arti" "Main Article"

 @{b}Main Article@{ub}

  Seen Babylon 5, the war scenes, the backgrounds? Its done on amiga as you
 know, and its done using Lightwave.

  If you've always wondered WHY they use Lightwave instead of Imagine, its
 because Imagine doesn't support networking. If it did, if could easily be
 in place, but it also has a MUCH slower key-framing system.

  I admit, I use Lightwave 5 and Imagine 5, and when it comes to animating,
 Lightwave 5 kicks butt, not only does it render quicker, it has moe control
 over the globals etc.

  But, when it comes to modeling, NOTHING beats Imagine. Lightwave is almost
 IMPOSSIBLE just to get a simple sphere out of the bloody thing, little
 alone a babylon 5 object!

  Perhaps it just takes practise, I know I can't get a hang of it.

  But Lightwave handles textures better, and it goes on.

  And Imagine hasn't got as good plug-ins (called "effects" in imagine).
 But thats the way it goes I guess.

  Babylon 5 is done a bunch of A2000's using 060 or 040 and I THINK their
 using cybergraphics (not sure).

  Babylon 5 (the object) consists of 30,000 polygons (faces) and takes up
 30 meg of HD SPACE! THATS MASSIVE! It would have to one of the most detailed
 space stations ever created, not to mention all the things like the Delta
 Fighters and the Membari Cruisers, who knows how big it is all together.
 The anims would be smaller than the objects combined in the end (the anims
 never go for too long, unless its a war episode).

 @{b}SEND IN YOUR ARTICLE NOW... JamieB5@Hotmail.com@{ub}

